# Attribute Information

# preg :- Number of times patient got pregnent

#  plas :- Plasma Glucose level of the patient 
#          (Normal :- Below 140 mg/dl, Diabetic:- More than 140 mg/dl)

# pres :- Blood Pressure of the patient (mm Hg) 
#       (Normal :- 60 to 90, High :- > 90, Low :- < 60)

# skin :- Triceps Skin fold Thickness of the patient (mm) 
#         (Normal Skin Thickness in Women is 23 mm.)

# test :- Two hour serum insulin test (mu U/ml)
#            (2 hour after Glucose serum Insulin level should be between 16-166 mu U/ml)

# mass :-Body mass index (Weight in kg / (hight in Meter)^2) 
#       (Normal :- 18.5 to 25, Over Weight :- More than 30)

# pedi :- Diabetes Pedigree function (Synthesis of the history of Diabetes Mellitus in relatives, generic)

# age :- Age (Years)

# Dclass :- Occurence of Diabetes (Yes = 1, No = 0)

# Defining a function to replace missing values with mean or median. 

def missingimput(col_name):
    mean = df1[col_name].mean()
    median = df1[col_name].median()
    mm_array =[mean,median]
    return mm_array

# Outlier removal

def outlier_detect(df1):
    for i in df1.describe().columns:
        Q1=df1.describe().at['25%',i]
        Q3=df1.describe().at['75%',i]
        IQR=Q3 - Q1
        LTV=Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
        UTV=Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
        x=np.array(df1[i])
        p=[]
        for j in x:
            if j < LTV or j>UTV:
                p.append(df1[i].mean())
            else:
                p.append(j)
        df1[i]=p
    return df1

def draw_cm_LR( y_test, y_pred ):
    cm_LR = metrics.confusion_matrix( y_test, y_pred )
    sns.heatmap(cm_LR, annot=True,  fmt='.2f', xticklabels = ["No Diabetic", "Diabetic"] , yticklabels = ["No Diabetic", "Diabetic"] )
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
    plt.show()

Step 11 :- Summary¶

1 :- Lot of missing values was present in dataset. 2 :- Lot of outlier were present in dataset. 3 :- Data was not normally distributed for most of the variables. 4 :- Non-Diabetic patients Sample size was much greater than Diabetic patients Sample size. Hence it was expected to get better prediction result for Non-Diabetic patients. 5 :- Glucose Level, Blood pressure, Body Mass Index, Number of Pregnency and Age seems to be the good indicators to predict Diabetes more accurately. 6 :- Diabetes Pedigree Function, Insulin Serum Level and skin thickness seems to be least useful indicators to predict the Diabetes. 7 :- Logistic Regression model performed better than Naive Bayes Model. 8 :- Accuracy of Logistic Regression :- 76.6% while Accuracy of Naive Bayes Model :- 73.16% 9 :- But Recall of Diabetic category was better in Naive Bayes 58.4 % than Logistic Regression 53.9 % 10 :- Hence to predict Non-Diabetic using Logistic Regression Model is better, while to predict Diabetic patients Naive Bayes Model is good. 11 :- More features in data set also required, like food habit, Oil, salt used in cooking etc.

Step 12 :- Conclusion :-¶

More samples needed for diabetic patients to predict more accuratly, Need to collect samples which has less missing values, More features in data set also required, like food habit, Oil, salt used in cooking etc, Logistic Regression and Naive bayes both model performed better for each category, but still need a model which can predict better than these models. Plasma, mass, age have good correlation while other veriables has very week correlation. Dataset is not very reliable to predict the Diabetes accurately due to lot of missing values and outliers.
